    <div class="faq">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What is the average institutional ownership across all US public companies?</h3>
            <p>Based on 2026 data, the average institutional ownership across US public companies is approximately 73.5%. This varies significantly by market capitalization and sector.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What does high institutional ownership mean?</h3>
            <p>High institutional ownership (typically &gt;80%) signals strong confidence from major funds and banks, implying stability, rigorous analysis backing the stock, and liquidity. However, extremely high levels (&gt;95%) can mean the stock is "crowded," leaving fewer marginal buyers and increasing the risk of sharp selloffs if institutions simultaneously exit.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What does low institutional ownership signal?</h3>
            <p>Low institutional ownership (often &lt;20%) could mean the company is undiscovered, too small, or operates in a highly speculative space. It can also indicate high insider or founder ownership. For investors, it may present an opportunity to "get in early" before institutional money drives up the price, albeit with higher risk and lower liquidity.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Which sectors have the highest institutional ownership?</h3>
            <p>Our 2026 analysis shows that sectors like Healthcare (81.9%) and Consumer Cyclical (80.5%) tend to attract the highest institutional capital due to reliable cash flows or strong growth characteristics.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How does market cap affect institutional ownership?</h3>
            <p>There is a direct correlation between market cap and institutional ownership. Mega-cap and large-cap stocks typically see higher average institutional ownership because large funds require massive liquidity to build positions without moving the market. Small and micro-cap stocks have noticeably lower institutional ownership.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Which stocks have the highest institutional ownership?</h3>
            <p>Typically, large-cap, established companies in the S&P 500 feature the highest institutional ownership percentages, often exceeding 80%. See our data table above for the exact 2026 figures.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What stocks do hedge funds own?</h3>
            <p>Hedge funds frequently target technology, healthcare, and consumer discretionary sectors, seeking high-growth opportunities or mispriced assets. Look at the "Top Holder" column in our table to see major institutional players.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What percentage of stocks are owned by institutions?</h3>
            <p>In the modern U.S. stock market, institutions collectively own approximately 70-80% of the market value of publicly traded companies, a figure that continues to remain strong in 2026.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="methodology">
        <h2>Methodology</h2>
        <p>This 2026 study analyzed a diverse cross-section of 818 US-listed equities, including all S&P 500 constituents and components of broader market indices spanning mega-cap to micro-cap companies. Data was sourced from public market filings via Yahoo Finance APIs. Averages presented are unweighted arithmetic means of the institutional ownership percentages within the respective cohorts. Invalid ownership percentages were bounded to standard constraints (0-100% for institutions, 0-80% for insiders). Data for informational purposes only.</p>
    </div>

